U.N. Security Council votes to call rare emergency General Assembly session on Ukraine

Abigail Williams
11d ago / 8:35 PM UTC

The U.N. Security Council voted Sunday to call a emergency special session of the General Assembly that will take place Monday, a rare move that comes as the U.S. and its allies, including the European Union, crack down on Moscow for its invasion of Ukraine.

The decision to call the session passed with 11 votes in favor. China, India and the United Arab Emirates abstained, and Russia was the lone vote against the resolution. Because it was a procedural vote, only nine votes were needed for it to pass, and Russia's veto did not apply.

"Russia cannot veto our voices. Russia cannot veto the Ukrainian people. Russia cannot veto the U.N. Charter. Russia cannot and will not veto accountability," said Linda Thomas-Greenfield, the U.S. ambassador to the U.N., calling the vote "an important step forward" toward holding Russia responsible for its actions. 

Thomas-Greenfield, addressing Russia and reports that its forces have targeted civilians in Ukraine, said the "world is watching."

"Photographic and video evidence is mounting, and you will be held to account for your actions. We will not let atrocities slide," she said.

